body: Followup to #5924 (@da-woods). The exit status of `Cython/Debugger/Tests/test_lib_cython_in_gdb.py` is currently ignored, but needed patching to run at all, at least in my docker environment.

comment_data.body: The class [uses](https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/b31623d5c049063849c7fd4cdf5e72be2ddcf4a7/Cython/Debugger/Tests/test_libcython_in_gdb.py#L55) a [six](https://six.readthedocs.io) based [method](https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/0e1026cb7c767450a88ab822e8eda2b451dee3c6/Cython/Utils.py#L587) to add a metaclass in a Python 2 and 3 compatible way. This results in the class inheriting only from the metaclass that created it. [Here is a StackOverflow question on the topic](https://stackoverflow.com/q/58475561/3476782).

comment_data.body:
In my testing environment, this part of the symbol table hadn't been loaded by the time this was executed. For reference, [`PyModuleObject` is defined here](https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/fd49e226700e2483a452c3c92da6f15d822ae054/Include/internal/pycore_moduleobject.h#L25). Not sure if it got moved since this was written or GDB started loading symbol tables more lazily. Regardless, it seems better practice to check that GDB has a symbol table corresponding to the executable rather than checking for the existence of a specific type, even if it is in the core definitions.

Does the original setup work on your setup? Was there something more specific you wanted a comment about? Here's documentation on [inferiors and progspaces](https://sourceware.org/gdb/current/onlinedocs/gdb.html/Inferiors-Connections-and-Programs.html) and on [the `symbol_file` attribute specifically](https://sourceware.org/gdb/current/onlinedocs/gdb.html/Progspaces-In-Python.html#index-Progspace_002esymbol_005ffile)

Then it's just a matter of wording. The words used in the expression are not very obvious (to me).
```suggestion
                    # Check if the Python executable provides a symbol table.
                    if not hasattr(gdb.selected_inferior().progspace, "symbol_file"):
```
